  "datePublished": "2025-12-31",
  "description": "An enriched category over a monoidal category V is a category-like structure whose hom-objects are objects of V rather than sets. An ordinary category is enriched over Set (with Cartesian product); replacing Set with a richer base V allows the morphisms between two objects to carry additional structure — topological, algebraic, or homotopical.\nAn enriched category C consists of: a collection of objects, for each pair (A, B) a hom-object Hom(A, B) in V, composition maps Hom(B, C) ⊗ Hom(A, B) → Hom(A, C) using the tensor product of V, and identity maps I → Hom(A, A) from the unit object. These must satisfy associativity and unit laws expressed as commutative diagrams in V.\n",
